::title::
# Long-running backends should feel like writing application code

::subtitle::
Not stitching together queues, retries, schedulers, and state machines by hand.

<!--
Use this slide as the thesis for the whole talk. Mention the typical picture people have in their heads when they hear "durable workflow": queues, workers, dead-letter handling, cron, retry settings, some dashboard in a different tool, and a lot of glue code. Then contrast that with the promise of Workflow: the orchestration is visible directly in the TypeScript they already know how to read.
-->
