::title::
# How to adopt Workflow incrementally

::s1-tag::
<Tag color="gray">Start Small</Tag>

::s1-title::
Pick one async path

::s1-body::
Choose a flow that already hurts: approvals, retries, delayed sends, or multi-step AI processing.

::s2-tag::
<Tag color="gray">Draw Boundaries</Tag>

::s2-title::
Mark the expensive edges

::s2-body::
Put model calls, external APIs, email sends, and side effects behind `use step`.

::s3-tag::
<Tag color="gray">Replace Glue</Tag>

::s3-title::
Keep your app, remove orchestration

::s3-body::
Start the workflow from your existing route or handler and let the platform manage durability underneath.

<!--
This is where you make the story actionable for people who are interested but cautious. Tell them not to "workflow-ify" their entire architecture at once. Instead, pick the one async path that already causes incidents, complexity, or product hesitation. Approvals, retries, delayed notifications, and multi-step AI calls are perfect starting points because the pain is usually visible already.
-->
---
---
layout: 10-code
variant: right-list
filename: next.config.ts
codeSize: sm
---

::code::
```ts
import { withWorkflow } from 'workflow/next';

const nextConfig = {};

export default withWorkflow(nextConfig);
```

::title::
# The setup story is intentionally small

::item-1::
Bring Workflow into the framework you already use

::item-2::
Keep routes, components, and deployment flow familiar

::item-3::
Add workflows where you need durability

::item-4::
Expand from one use case to many

<!--
Use this slide to lower the activation energy. Mention that the framework integration is deliberately lightweight and designed so teams can stay inside the framework they already use. This is also a good moment to mention framework breadth and the examples repo if you want the audience to feel there is a path whether they are in Next.js or elsewhere.
-->
---
